# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chord-diagrams
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In graph theory and computer science, an **adjacency matrix** is a square matrix used to represent a finite graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The elements of the matrix indicate whether pairs of vertices are adjacent or not within the graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In the special case of a finite simple graph, the adjacency matrix is a (0,1)-matrix with zeros on its diagonal.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] If the graph is undirected (i.e. all of its edges are bidirectional), the adjacency matrix is symmetric.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The relationship between a graph and the eigenvalues and eigenvectors of its adjacency matrix is studied in spectral graph theory.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a graph should be distinguished from its incidence matrix, a different matrix representation whose elements indicate whether vertex–edge pairs are incident or not, and its degree matrix, which contains information about the degree of each vertex.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] For a simple graph with vertex set *U* = {*u*1, ..., *u**n*}, the adjacency matrix is a square *n* × *n* matrix A such that its element Aij is 1 when there is an edge from vertex *u*i to vertex *u*j, and 0 when there is no edge.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The diagonal elements of the matrix are all 0, since edges from a vertex to itself (loops) are not allowed in simple graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] It is also sometimes useful in algebraic graph theory to replace the nonzero elements with algebraic variables.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The same concept can be extended to multigraphs and graphs with loops by storing the number of edges between each two vertices in the corresponding matrix element, and by allowing nonzero diagonal elements.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Loops may be counted either once (as a single edge) or twice (as two vertex-edge incidences), as long as a consistent convention is followed.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Undirected graphs often use the latter convention of counting loops twice, whereas directed graphs typically use the former convention.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] where B is an *r* × *s* matrix, and 0*r*,*r* and 0*s*,*s* represent the *r* × *r* and *s* × *s* zero matrices.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In this case, the smaller matrix B uniquely represents the graph, and the remaining parts of A can be discarded as redundant.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] B is sometimes called the *biadjacency matrix*.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The biadjacency matrix is the *r* × *s* 0–1 matrix B in which *b**i*,*j* = 1 if and only if (*u**i*, *v**j*) ∈ *E*.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] If G is a bipartite multigraph or weighted graph, then the elements b*i,j* are taken to be the number of edges between the vertices or the weight of the edge (*u**i*, *v**j*), respectively.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] An (*a*, *b*, *c*)-adjacency matrix A of a simple graph has *A**i*,*j* = *a* if (*i*, *j*) is an edge, b if it is not, and c on the diagonal.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The Seidel adjacency matrix is a (−1, 1, 0)-adjacency matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] This matrix is used in studying strongly regular graphs and two-graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix has in position (*i*, *j*) the distance between vertices vi and vj.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The distance is the length of a shortest path connecting the vertices.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Unless lengths of edges are explicitly provided, the length of a path is the number of edges in it.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The distance matrix resembles a high power of the adjacency matrix, but instead of telling only whether or not two vertices are connected (i.e., the connection matrix, which contains Boolean values), it gives the exact distance between them.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The convention followed here (for undirected graphs) is that each edge adds 1 to the appropriate cell in the matrix, and each loop (an edge from a vertex to itself) adds 2 to the appropriate cell on the diagonal in the matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] This allows the degree of a vertex to be easily found by taking the sum of the values in either its respective row or column in the adjacency matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a directed graph can be asymmetric.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The former definition is commonly used in graph theory and social network analysis (e.g., sociology, political science, economics, psychology).
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The latter is more common in other applied sciences (e.g., dynamical systems, physics, network science) where A is sometimes used to describe linear dynamics on graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Using the first definition, the in-degrees of a vertex can be computed by summing the entries of the corresponding column and the out-degree of vertex by summing the entries of the corresponding row.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] When using the second definition, the in-degree of a vertex is given by the corresponding row sum and the out-degree is given by the corresponding column sum.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of a complete graph contains all ones except along the diagonal where there are only zeros.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an empty graph is a zero matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix of an undirected simple graph is symmetric, and therefore has a complete set of real eigenvalues and an orthogonal eigenvector basis.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The set of eigenvalues of a graph is the **spectrum** of the graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The greatest eigenvalue $\lambda _{1}$ is bounded above by the maximum degree.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] This can be seen as result of the Perron–Frobenius theorem, but it can be proved easily.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Let v be one eigenvector associated to $\lambda _{1}$ and x the entry in which v has maximum absolute value.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Without loss of generality assume vx is positive since otherwise you simply take the eigenvector -v, also associated to $\lambda _{1}$ .
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] For d-regular graphs, d is the first eigenvalue of A for the vector *v* = (1, ..., 1) (it is easy to check that it is an eigenvalue and it is the maximum because of the above bound).
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The multiplicity of this eigenvalue is the number of connected components of G, in particular $\lambda _{1}>\lambda _{2}$ for connected graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] It can be shown that for each eigenvalue $\lambda _{i}$ , its opposite $-\lambda _{i}=\lambda _{n+1-i}$ is also an eigenvalue of A if G is a bipartite graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In particular −d is an eigenvalue of any d-regular bipartite graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The difference $\lambda _{1}-\lambda _{2}$ is called the spectral gap and it is related to the expansion of G.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] It is also useful to introduce the spectral radius of A denoted by $\lambda (G)=\max _{\left|\lambda _{i}\right|<d}|\lambda _{i}|$ .
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] This bound is tight in the Ramanujan graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Suppose two directed or undirected graphs *G*1 and *G*2 with adjacency matrices *A*1 and *A*2 are given.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In particular, *A*1 and *A*2 are similar and therefore have the same minimal polynomial, characteristic polynomial, eigenvalues, determinant and trace.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] These can therefore serve as isomorphism invariants of graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] However, two graphs may possess the same set of eigenvalues but not be isomorphic.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Such linear operators are said to be isospectral.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] If A is the adjacency matrix of the directed or undirected graph G, then the matrix *A**n* (i.e., the matrix product of n copies of A) has an interesting interpretation: the element (*i*, *j*) gives the number of (directed or undirected) walks of length n from vertex i to vertex j.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] If n is the smallest nonnegative integer, such that for some i, j, the element (*i*, *j*) of *A**n* is positive, then n is the distance between vertex i and vertex j.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] A great example of how this is useful is in counting the number of triangles in an undirected graph G, which is exactly the trace of *A*3 divided by 3 or 6 depending on whether the graph is directed or not.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] We divide by those values to compensate for the overcounting of each triangle.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In an undirected graph, each triangle will be counted twice for all three nodes, because the path can be followed clockwise or counterclockwise : ijk or ikj.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix can be used to determine whether or not the graph is connected.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] If a directed graph has a nilpotent adjacency matrix (i.e., if there exists n such that *A**n* is the zero matrix), then it is a directed acyclic graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The adjacency matrix may be used as a data structure for the representation of graphs in computer programs for manipulating graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Boolean data types are used, such as `True` and `False` in Python.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The main alternative data structure, also in use for this application, is the adjacency list.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] The space needed to represent an adjacency matrix and the time needed to perform operations on them is dependent on the matrix representation chosen for the underlying matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Sparse matrix representations only store non-zero matrix entries and implicitly represent the zero entries.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] They can, for example, be used to represent sparse graphs without incurring the space overhead from storing the many zero entries in the adjacency matrix of the sparse graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] In the following section the adjacency matrix is assumed to be represented by an array data structure so that zero and non-zero entries are all directly represented in storage.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Although slightly more succinct representations are possible, this method gets close to the information-theoretic lower bound for the minimum number of bits needed to represent all n-vertex graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] For storing graphs in text files, fewer bits per byte can be used to ensure that all bytes are text characters, for instance by using a Base64 representation.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Besides avoiding wasted space, this compactness encourages locality of reference.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] However, for a large sparse graph, adjacency lists require less storage space, because they do not waste any space representing edges that are *not* present.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] An alternative form of adjacency matrix (which, however, requires a larger amount of space) replaces the numbers in each element of the matrix with pointers to edge objects (when edges are present) or null pointers (when there is no edge).
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] It is also possible to store edge weights directly in the elements of an adjacency matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Besides the space tradeoff, the different data structures also facilitate different operations.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] Finding all vertices adjacent to a given vertex in an adjacency list is as simple as reading the list, and takes time proportional to the number of neighbors.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] With an adjacency matrix, an entire row must instead be scanned, which takes a larger amount of time, proportional to the number of vertices in the whole graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/adjacency-matrix] On the other hand, testing whether there is an edge between two given vertices can be determined at once with an adjacency matrix, while requiring time proportional to the minimum degree of the two vertices with the adjacency list.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] A **chord diagram** is a graphical method of displaying the inter-relationships between data in a matrix.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The data are arranged radially around a circle with the relationships between the data points typically drawn as arcs connecting the data.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The format can be aesthetically pleasing, making it a popular choice in the world of data visualization.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The primary use of chord diagrams is to show the flows or connections between several entities (called nodes).
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Each entity is represented by a fragment (often colored or pattered) along the circumference of the circle.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Arcs are drawn between entities to show flows (and exchanges in economics).
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] The thickness of the arc is proportional to the significance of the flow.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Chord diagrams get their name from terminology used in geometry.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] A chord of a circle is a geometric line segment whose endpoints both lie on the circle.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Chord diagrams are also known as **radial network diagrams** and may sometimes be referred to as a type of circular layout.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] While a small amount of data could be represented in a circular diagram using straight lines to show the interconnections, a diagram featuring numerous lines would quickly become illegible.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] To reduce the visual complexity, chord diagrams employ a technique called hierarchical edge bundling.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] Chord diagrams are useful for showing relationships between entities and their relative magnitudes in comparison to alternative arcs.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] As a result, chord diagrams are popular in migration studies, economic flows, and genome studies.
[src:chord-diagrams/chord-diagram-information-visualization] They have also been used to highlight unexplored relationships to help address the problem of filter bubbles.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] In graph drawing, a **circular layout** is a style of drawing that places the vertices of a graph on a circle, often evenly spaced so that they form the vertices of a regular polygon.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] Circular layouts are a good fit for communications network topologies such as star or ring networks, and for the cyclic parts of metabolic networks.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] For graphs with a known Hamiltonian cycle, a circular layout allows the cycle to be depicted as the circle, and in this way circular layouts form the basis of the LCF notation for Hamiltonian cubic graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] A circular layout may be used on its own for an entire graph drawing, but it also may be used as the layout for smaller clusters of vertices within a larger graph drawing, such as its biconnected components, clusters of genes in a gene interaction graph, or natural subgroups within a social network.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] If multiple vertex circles are used in this way, other methods such as force-directed graph drawing may be used to arrange the clusters.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] The edges of the drawing may be depicted as chords of the circle, as circular arcs (possibly perpendicular to the vertex circle, so that the edges model lines of the Poincaré disk model of hyperbolic geometry), or as other types of curve.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] The visual distinction between the inside and the outside of the vertex circle in a circular layout may be used to separate two different styles of edge drawing.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] For instance, a circular drawing algorithm of Gansner & Koren (2007) uses edge bundling within the circle, together with some edges that are not bundled, drawn outside the circle.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] For circular layouts of regular graphs, with edges drawn both inside and outside as circular arcs, the angle of incidence of one of these arcs with the vertex circle is the same at both ends of the arc, a property that simplifies the optimization of the angular resolution of the drawing.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] Several authors have studied the problem of finding a permutation of the vertices of a circular layout that minimizes the number of edge crossings when all edges are drawn inside the vertex circle.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] This number of crossings is zero only for outerplanar graphs.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] For other graphs, it may be optimized or reduced separately for each biconnected component of the graph before combining the solutions, as these components may be drawn so that they do not interact.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] In general, minimizing the number of crossings is NP-complete.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] (1995) described an approximation algorithm based on balanced cuts or edge separators, subsets of few edges whose removal disconnects the given graph into two subgraphs with approximately equal numbers of vertices.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] After finding an approximate cut, their algorithm arranges the two subgraphs on each side of the cut recursively, without considering the additional crossings formed by the edges that cross the cut.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] Their work cites a paper by Fan Chung and Shing-Tung Yau from 1994 that claimed $\rho =O(1)$ , but this was later found to have an erroneous proof.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] Instead, the best approximation known for the balanced cut problem has $\rho =O({\sqrt {\log n}})$ , giving this circular layout algorithm an approximation ratio of $O(\log ^{3}n)$ on graphs that have a large number of crossings relative to their vertex degrees.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] Heuristic methods for reducing the crossing complexity have also been devised, based e.g. on a careful vertex insertion order and on local optimization.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] A circular layout may also be used to maximize the number of crossings.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] In particular, choosing a random permutation for the vertices causes each possible crossing to occur with probability 1/3, so the expected number of crossings is within a factor of three of the maximum number of crossings among all possible layouts.
[src:chord-diagrams/circular-layout] Derandomizing this method gives a deterministic approximation algorithm with approximation ratio three.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] A **radial tree**, or **radial map**, is a method of displaying a tree structure (e.g., a tree data structure) in a way that expands outwards, radially.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] It is one of many ways to visually display a tree, with examples dating back to the early 20th century.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] In use, it is a type of information graphic.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] The overall distance "d" is the distance between levels of the graph.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] It is chosen so that the overall layout will fit within a screen.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] Layouts are generated by working outward from the center, root.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] The first level is a special case because all the nodes have the same parent.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] The nodes for level 1 can be distributed evenly, or weighted depending on the number of children they have.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] For subsequent levels, the children are positioned within sectors of the remaining space, so that child nodes of one parent do not overlap with others.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] There are many extensions to this algorithm to create more visually balanced layouts, to allow users to navigate from node to node (changing the center), or accommodate node labels and combine force-directed layouts with radial layouts.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] The layout has some similarities to a hyperbolic tree, though a key difference is that hyperbolic trees are based on hyperbolic geometry, whereas in a radial tree the distance between orbits is relatively linear.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] In a simple case, the first node is at the top, and the linked nodes are beneath.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] As each node typically has more than one child, the resulting shape is relatively triangular.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] In a radial layout, instead of each successive generation being displayed a row below, each generation is displayed in a new, outer orbit.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] Since the length of each orbit increases with the radius, there tends to be more room for the nodes.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] A radial tree will spread the larger number of nodes over a larger area as the levels increase.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] We use the terms level and depth interchangeably.
[src:chord-diagrams/radial-tree] Nevertheless, the number of nodes increases exponentially with the distance from the first node, whereas the circumference of each orbit increases linearly, so, by the outer orbits, the nodes tend to be packed together.
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] The project was started in 2013 by a group of researchers of Politecnico di Milano with the original name of "RAW".
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] In the same year the tool won the "Most Beautiful" award at the Kantar Information is Beautiful Awards 2014 organized by David McCandless.
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] In 2017 the project was re-launched thanks to private support.
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] It changed the license from LGPL to Apache 2 and the project name to "RAWGraphs".
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] In August 2019 the team launched a crowdfunding campaign to harvest economical support for developing a new version of the tool.
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] Version 2.0.0 was released in September 2020 to backers, and publicly in February 2021.
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] The new version presents a modular architecture composed by a core JavaScript library, an expandable library of visual models, and a web-based GUI written in React.
[src:chord-diagrams/rawgraphs] RAWGraphs has been used in a number of research projects in academia, and is used also by journalist and graphic designer thanks to its ability of creating clean, SVG-based images that can be further edited with any other software.
